@acmepjz Please apologize for the long silence. I was out of the office for a few days. Before I say anything else: thanks for considering my PR so carefully!

 If the maintainers feel that going from  to a topological space is a good idea, I won't stand in their way. I am however still hesitant because I am concerned that the general definition might be misleading. As you point out, the current definition will work for Riemann surfaces. However, it will not work in higher dimensions, where a divisor is an entirely different object. It will not work on singular spaces, where one needs the proper distinction between Weil divisors and Cartier divisors instead of the simplistic definition that works for subsets of .

To make matters worse, I am under the impression that the proper definition of "divisor" is not a matter of the topological space alone. Take the complex plane. As a complex analytic space, the complex plane is one-dimensional and the current definition is the correct one. Seen as a real analytic space, the complex plane is two-dimensional and the current definition will not work. IMHO this implies that the choice of the field must be part of the data when one defines the notion of divisor.

@acmepjz Thanks again. Please let me refer you to my comments further up on my concerns about using topological spaces.

Value distribution theory is used today in the context of work on Lang's conjecture, to study entire curves in compact Khler manifolds as an analog of rational points on an algebraic variety. There is a subject "hyperbolic Nevanlinna theory" that generalizes entire curves, studying holomorphic functions whose domain is a cover of the complex plane. There is a substantial body of work generalizing all this to the higher-dimensional setting, and to link the theory with the dynamics of foliations on complex manifolds.

All these matters are completely out of scope for the moment. As far as I know, there is not even a well-developed theory of Khler manifolds that would be required to even state the relevant results. For now, I am trying to work on the very basics, covering the most elementary case only for later work to build on.

```suggestion
theorem nhdNE_of_nhdNE_sdiff_finite {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] [T1Space X] {x : X}
```
